<h1>Assignment: Basic Design Principles of a Mobile Web page</h1>

<h2>Assignment 2A</h2>

<p>During this assignment we will make the design of a web page about Beethoven's <em>Ode to Joy</em> mobile friendly.
On various mobile browsers, the page is zoomed out and required zoom in then double scrolling to be read.</p>

<a href="original/sample.html">Web page original version</a>

<h2>Step A: Remove double scrolling</h2>

<p>The following modifications are applied at this step:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Add the <tt>&lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1.0"/&gt;</tt> tag.</li>
  <li>Resize image <tt>beethoven.jpg</tt> to 120x150 and cropp + resize <tt>beethoven-background.jpg</tt> to 120x18.</li>
  <li>Changed the sidebar from left float to block, making the page linear with a liquid layout.</li>
</ul>

<p>To make the table more usable on a mobile device, I've applied these adaptations:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The "Symphony" column header is renamed "Symphony nÂ°" and the word Symphony is removed from following rows.</li>
  <li>The the word "Op." is removed from the rows following the header "Op.".</li>
  <li>Padding of each cell is reduced</li>
  <li>Border tables collapse in CSS (<tt>border-collapse: collapse;</tt>) so we gain separation space between cells.</li>
</ul>

